# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2009-major-league-baseball-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The **1876 major league baseball season** was contested from April 22 through October 21, 1876, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the inaugural season of the National League and of Major League baseball.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Two non-NA teams would join as charter members, including the Cincinnati Reds (unrelated to the modern team) and Louisville Grays.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The 1876 schedule was formatted so that each team would play up to 10 games against each team in the league (split evenly between home and away games), for a maximum of 70 games (only fulfilled by the Boston Red Caps).
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Any game played against a team at home must be played within two months' time away, "under penalty of forfeiture." This was the only season that the National League adopted this format.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see a more regulated format, requiring teams to schedule 12 games against each team.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 22 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Athletics of Philadelphia.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 21, featuring a game between the Hartford Dark Blues and Boston Red Caps.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The first doubleheader in major league history occurred on September 9 between the Cincinnati Reds and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The year ended with the first postseason competition in major league history.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The contest featured the first and second-place regular season finishers.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Three tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Grays had three tie games.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues, New York Mutuals, and Philadelphia Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues would play their final game at the Hartford Ball Club Grounds on September 16 against the St.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings, relocating to Brooklyn, New York at the Union Grounds as the Brooklyn Hartfords for the start of the 1877 season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The **1877 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through October 6, 1877, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the second season of the National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1876, two teams were formally kicked out of the league for failing to fulfill their schedules: New York Mutuals and Philadelphia Athletics, contracting the league from eight to six teams.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blue would relocate from Hartford, Connecticut to Brooklyn, New York, as the Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The 1877 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other five teams in the league.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season that the National League adopted the format.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The format would last only through the following season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 6, featuring four teams.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords had two tie games.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Louisville Grays had one tie game each.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings would play their final game at 23rd Street Grounds on October 6 against the Louisville Grays, moving to Lakefront Park for the start of the 1878 season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game against the Chicago White Stockings on their last home game of the season, September 22, at the site of the former National Association's New Haven Elm Citys, at the Howard Avenue Grounds in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The **1878 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1878, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the third season of the National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1877, two teams would fold: Brooklyn Hartfords and St.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] They were replaced by the Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Later in the offseason, the Providence Grays would join on February 6, raising the number of teams to seven.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] On April 1 or 2, the Louisville Grays would officially resign from the league, once again lowering the number of teams to six.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The 1878 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] This format had been in place since the previous season, and would be the final season which saw this format, due to expansion to eight teams the following season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all six teams.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Two teams hosted games at neutral sites, the Indianapolis Blues and Providence Grays.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Four tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues had three tie games.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Milwaukee Grays had one tie game each.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings leave the 23rd Street Grounds (where they played for four seasons since their National Association days from 1874) and move to Lakefront Park where they would play for seven seasons through 1884.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The **1879 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1879, and saw the Providence Grays as the pennant winner of the fourth season of the National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the National League was set on expanding from a six-team league to an eight-team league.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays folded, and in its place, the league admitted the Cleveland Blues, the International Association's Buffalo Bisons and Syracuse Stars, and finally (with confirmation Milwaukee was not returning) the Troy Trojans.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] It is suggested by Society for American Baseball Research (SABR) that this season featured the first African-American to play major league baseball, William Edward White, who played one game with the Providence Grays on June 21.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] He predates brothers Moses Fleetwood Walker and Weldy Walker by five years, and Jackie Robinson by 68 years.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The 1879 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] This format was an adjustment to the 12-games-each format that had been in place since 1877, as the National League expanded from six to eight teams, adding 24 games to each team's schedule.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring six teams.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Five tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings had four tie games.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Reds, Providence Grays, and Syracuse Stars had one tie game each.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans would play their final game at the Putnam Grounds on September 20 against the Chicago White Stockings, moving to Haymakers' Grounds for the start of the 1880 season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The **1880 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 1, 1880, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the fifth season of the National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 season is known for the first two major league perfect games in history, as well as being the only perfect games in the 19th century.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Thrown by Lee Richmond and John Ward, these two perfect games were thrown in the span of five days, the shortest amount of time between two perfect games (the next closest is currently 20 days between Dallas Braden's May 9 and Roy Halladay's and May 29, 2010 perfect games).
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] A perfect game would not be seen again in the Major Leagues for 24 years when Cy Young threw his perfect game in 1904.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the Cincinnati Reds and Syracuse Stars disbanded, and were replaced by the Cincinnati Stars and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the Stars' only major league season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the previous season and would be used until 1883.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 1, featuring a doubleheader between the Providence Grays and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Eight tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Stars, and Providence Grays had three tie games each.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, and Worcester Worcesters had two tie games each.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave the Putnam Grounds (where they played their inaugural seasons) and move to the Haymakers' Grounds, where they would play for two seasons through 1881.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans begin to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing on September 11.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The **1881 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through September 30, 1881, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the sixth season of the National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The 1881 season is most known for featuring the first major league grand slam.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Roger Connor of the Troy Trojans hit the walk-off home run at Riverside Park (Greenbush) against the Worcester Worcesters on September 10, leading to an 8–7 victory.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the National League dropped the Cincinnati Stars because the team refused to sign a league pledge that banned alcohol in league parks and forbade clubs from renting their parks out on Sundays.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The team was replaced by the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] 1881 would be the final season of the first National League monopoly-era, as the American Association would be established in 1882.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The 1881 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since 1879 and would be used until 1883.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring four teams.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring all eight teams.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Two tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues, Providence Grays, Troy Trojans, and Worcester Worcesters had one tie game each.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines join the National League and play at Recreation Park in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans would play their final game at Haymakers' Grounds on September 30 against the Detroit Wolverines, moving to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds for the start of the 1882 season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing on June 15 and September 10.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The **2009 Major League Baseball season** began on April 5, 2009; the regular season was extended two days for a one-game playoff between the Detroit Tigers and the Minnesota Twins for the American League Central title.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began the next day with the Division Series.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series began on October 28, and ended on November 4, with the New York Yankees defeating the Philadelphia Phillies in six games.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second time the season was completed in November.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The only other occasion was the 2001 World Series, because of the delaying of the end of that season due to the September 11 attacks as November baseball would be guaranteed when Game 4 was played on Sunday, November 1.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Had the 2009 World Series gone the full seven games, Game 7 would've been played on November 5, the latest date ever scheduled for a World Series game.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] It became the latest date for a World Series game in 2022.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The American League champion had home field advantage for the World Series by virtue of winning the All-Star Game on July 14 at Busch Stadium in St.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In addition, the annual Civil Rights Game became a regular season game, and was played June 20 at Great American Ball Park in Cincinnati, Ohio, when the host Cincinnati Reds lost to the Chicago White Sox in an interleague game, 10–8.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Both teams wore replicas of their 1965 uniforms in the contest.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Note: Two teams in the same division could not meet in the division series.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Seattle Mariners named Milwaukee Brewers scouting director Jack Zduriencik its new general manager on October 22, replacing interim GM Lee Pelekoudas.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Washington Nationals GM Jim Bowden resigned on March 1 amid allegations that he was skimming bonus money from Latin American players.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Team president Stan Kasten first took over the bulk of his duties before transferring them to assistant GM Mike Rizzo, who had served as acting GM, and was named as the full-time general manager on August 20.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] During the last days of the regular season, two teams fired their general managers, effective at the end of the season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] On October 3, the Toronto Blue Jays fired J.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The following day, the San Diego Padres axed Kevin Towers, who had been the longest-tenured GM in Major League Baseball at 14 seasons.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Cito Gaston and Jerry Manuel both entered their first full season as managers of the Toronto Blue Jays and New York Mets, respectively, after taking over for managers dismissed in the middle of the 2008 season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Gaston had previously been the Blue Jays' manager from 1989 until 1997.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] On January 15, the owners of the 30 Major League Baseball clubs approved two rule changes governing the playing of postseason and one-game playoff games.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The 2009 season marked the opening of two new stadiums, both in New York City; Citi Field for the Mets and the new Yankee Stadium for the Yankees.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] They respectively replaced Shea Stadium (which was dismantled during the 2008–09 offseason) and the original Yankee Stadium (which became a public park after its demolition).
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Because of the smaller seating capacities in these new parks, Dodger Stadium is now the largest capacity park in use with 56,000 seats, and is also the third oldest ballpark in Major League Baseball behind Fenway Park and Wrigley Field.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Citi Field opened with a night game on April 13 as the Mets hosted the San Diego Padres losing 6–5.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In that game, Jody Gerut of the Padres became the first player in major league history to open a new ballpark with a leadoff homer.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Three days later, the Cleveland Indians inaugurated New Yankee Stadium against the Bronx Bombers.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] On Jackie Robinson Day (April 15), a rotunda at Citi Field was named in honor of Jackie Robinson and was dedicated prior to the Mets–Padres game that day.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The 2009 season also marked the final season of the Hubert H.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Humphrey Metrodome as the home for the Minnesota Twins, where they had played since 1982.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In 2010, the team moved to Target Field, their new baseball-only stadium located a short distance across town.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, since moving from Washington, D.C. in 1961, the franchise has shared, first Metropolitan Stadium, and then the Metrodome with the NFL's Minnesota Vikings; they also shared tenant rights at the Metrodome with the University of Minnesota's football team.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Golden Gophers started to play on-campus at TCF Bank Stadium in 2009.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Metrodome's last scheduled regular season game was to be played on Sunday, October 4, 2009, but the Twins tied the Detroit Tigers necessitating a one-game playoff between the two teams on October 6.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] While not a new stadium, Kansas City's Kauffman Stadium completed a two-year renovation.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The first year saw a new video board dubbed "Crown Vision" and refitting of several sections.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Improvements for 2009 include a new glass and brick facade to the exterior of the ballpark, newly expanded team Hall of Fame, a new sports bar/restaurant, improved sightlines, new luxury suites and refurbished press and radio/TV facilities to name a few.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In late March, the Florida Marlins had their funding for a new stadium at the former site of the Miami Orange Bowl approved by Miami-Dade County commissioners.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Groundbreaking ceremonies were held on July 18, with an opening by 2012, at which time the team will be renamed the **Miami Marlins**.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] This would have marked the first full season in the US for baseball games to be telecast as the transition from analog to digital television that was to have been made on February 17.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] However, the transition took place June 12.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] MLB was the last of the four major team sports to start its own television channel.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In Canada, Toronto Blue Jays games will be televised on Rogers Sportsnet and TSN.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] RSN also holds the Canadian rights to air the Fox and ESPN/ESPN2 games if they do not conflict with Blue Jays games, as well as the All-Star Game and the entire postseason.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In Australia free to air channel One HD shows up to 5 games live per week, and European channel ESPN America broadcasts games as well.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] ESPN Radio served as MLB's national radio network, broadcasting *Sunday Night Baseball* as well as selected Saturday and holiday games during the regular season, the Home Run Derby and All-Star Game, and all postseason series.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] As stated earlier, the Mets and Yankees wore patches commemorating the inaugural seasons of their new parks, the Twins wore patches commemorating their final season at the Metrodome, and the Cardinals, hosting the All-Star Game, wore a patch to celebrate that event.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Pittsburgh Pirates, Detroit Tigers, Oakland Athletics and Chicago White Sox led the Majors in wearing throwback uniforms.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] On May 2 at Safeco Field, the Athletics and Seattle Mariners honored 1939 by wearing special uniforms.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Mariners honored the Seattle Rainiers and the Oakland Athletics honored the Oakland Oaks from that season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Both teams played in the Pacific Coast League that season.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The A's then wore a 1980s styled uniform in St.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Petersburg on July 11 against the Tampa Bay Rays, who wore uniforms from their inaugural season of 1998 when they were known as the "Devil Rays".
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Finally, On August 16, the Athletics and White Sox used vintage throwbacks.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The A's wore uniforms from their Philadelphia period, with blue caps and a large A on the front of their jerseys.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The White Sox wore their jerseys with a large S with a lowercase O in the top loop and a lowercase X in the bottom loop.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] On June 14, the Tigers and Pirates wore throwback uniforms to commemorate the 100th anniversary of both Forbes Field and the 1909 World Series between the two teams.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] That game also featured a throwback atmosphere: no music or flashy graphics, no mascots (meaning no Jolly Roger or Pirate Parrot), and a hand-operated scoreboard.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] One modern item occurred in the pre-game: The Stanley Cup champion Pittsburgh Penguins made a surprise visit and brought the trophy with them.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Pirates and the Kansas City Royals also honored the Negro leagues on June 26 and 27 with the Pirates wearing the Homestead Grays uniforms and the Royals donning Kansas City Monarchs replicas.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Pirates and the Cincinnati Reds recreated their 1979 National League Championship Series uniforms on August 21 as part of the Buccos' 30th anniversary celebration of their World Series championship.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Bucs wore their gold pillbox hat with a gold jersey and black pants, a faux pas from the uniforms that season as a black cap was worn that year with the gold jersey.
[src:2009-major-league-baseball-season/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Tigers and the Cleveland Indians played in Negro league replicas twice, with the Tigers in Detroit Stars uniforms, and the Indians outfitted in Cleveland Buckeyes replicas.
